<section xml:id="section-making-graphs">
    <title>Making Graphs</title>

    <p>Let's put it all together and produce some graphs.</p>

    <exercises>
        <exercisegroup by="row" xml:id="exercisegroup-sketch-first">
            <introduction>
                <p>Consider the function <m>\fe{f}{x}=\frac{8x^2-8}{(2x-4)^2}</m>.</p>
            </introduction>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-sketch-first-asymptotes">
                <statement>
                    <p>Evaluate each of the following limits: <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\fe{f}{x}</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{x\to-\infty}\fe{f}{x}</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{x\to2^{-}}\fe{f}{x}</m>, and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to2^{+}}\fe{f}{x}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>What are the horizontal and vertical asymptotes for <m>f</m>'s graph?</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>What are the horizontal and vertical intercepts for <m>f</m>'s graph?</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-sketch-first-critical-numbers">
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the formulas <m>\fe{\fd{f}}{x}=\frac{4(1-2x)}{(x-2)^3}</m> and <m>\fe{\sd{f}}{x}=\frac{4(4x+1)}{(x-2)^4}</m> to help you accomplish each of the following.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>State the critical numbers of <m>f</m>.</li>
                        <li>Create well-documented increasing/decreasing and concavity tables for <m>f</m>.</li> 
                        <li>State the local minimum, local maximum, and inflection points on <m>f</m>.  Make sure that you explicitly address all three types of points whether they exist or not.</li> 
                    </ul>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Graph <m>y=\fe{f}{x}</m> onto <xref ref="figure-blank-for-graphing-1"/>. Choose a scale that allows you to clearly illustrate each of the features found in <xref autoname="plural" ref="exercise-sketch-first-asymptotes"/><ndash/><xref autoname="no" ref="exercise-sketch-first-critical-numbers"/>.  Label all axes and asymptotes well and write the coordinates of each local extreme point and inflection point next to the point.</p>
                    <figure xml:id="figure-blank-for-graphing-1">
                        <caption><m>f</m></caption>
                        <image>
                            <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[blankgraph]
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                            </latex-image-code>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-check-graph">
                <statement>
                    <p>Check your graph using a graphing calculator.</p>
                </statement>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Repeat <xref ref="exercisegroup-sketch-first"/> for the function <m>\fe{g}{t}=\frac{1}{(e^t+4)^2}</m>. Use the formulas <m>\fe{\fd{g}}{t}=\frac{-2e^t}{(e^t+4)^3}</m> and <m>\fe{\sd{g}}{t}=\frac{4e^t(e^t-2)}{(e^t+4)^4}</m>.</p>
                <figure xml:id="figure-blank-for-graphing-2">
                    <caption><m>g</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[blankgraph]
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
</section>
